            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Nadia Khalil\u2019s life is a study in elegant synthesis, a blend of the pragmatic and the poetic she inherited from her Lebanese-American parents in Dearborn, Michigan. Her father, a civil engineer, filled his workshop with blueprints and the scent of sawdust, teaching her that function was paramount. Her mother, a homemaker with an artist\u2019s soul, filled their home with intricate embroidery and the aroma of seven-spice, showing her that beauty was a language of its own. Nadia spent her youth navigating these two worlds, sketching beautiful, impossible machines in the margins of her math notebooks.\n\nThis duality found its purpose at the Pratt Institute in New York, where she pursued her MFA in Industrial Design. New York honed her ambition, but after a decade and the slow, amicable end of a long-term relationship, she craved a different kind of energy. A lead product designer role at a sustainable housewares company in San Francisco offered the perfect catalyst for change.\n\nNow, at 40, Nadia\u2019s life is shaped by the city\u2019s rhythms. Her 2.8-mile bicycle commute from her art-filled apartment in the Mission to her SoMa office is a daily ritual. Pedaling past vibrant murals and the morning bustle, she finds solutions to design problems\u2014how to make a recycled polymer feel warm, or how to craft a flat-pack chair that is both sturdy and graceful. Her work, creating beautiful, functional objects for everyday life, is a direct homage to her upbringing.\n\nHer social life is a tight-knit circle of fellow creatives and cyclists, often meeting for gallery openings or sharing meals at friends\u2019 homes. While she values her independence, Nadia dreams of launching her own design studio, one focused entirely on biomaterials and circular economies. She feels an immense connection to San Francisco\u2014a city that, like her, embraces innovation without discarding its soul. It is a place where a daughter of an engineer and an artist can finally feel perfectly, functionally, and beautifully at home."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was nine, smuggling one of her mother\u2019s date-filled ma\u2019amoul cookies into her father\u2019s workshop. The scent of buttery semolina and rose water met the sharp fragrance of pine sawdust. Her father, pausing over a blueprint, took the cookie, examined its delicate pattern, and then ate it in two thoughtful bites. He simply nodded, a blueprint in one hand and crumbs on his lips. It was the first time she understood that intricate beauty and clean function could\u2014and should\u2014share the same space.\n\n2.\nA month after she and David packed his last box in their Brooklyn apartment, she walked across the Williamsburg Bridge at dusk. The ache of their decade together was real, but so was the crisp autumn air and the endless grid of city lights. Instead of feeling diminished, she felt a quiet expansion. She wasn't just leaving a relationship; she was stepping onto a new, unburdened plane. The amicable split hadn\u2019t broken her, it had given her back a sense of clean, structural integrity.\n\n3.\nHer first week in San Francisco, pedaling down Valencia Street, felt like a sensory overload. The sheer density of it\u2014the vibrant murals, the sizzle of taquerias, the sudden, steep incline of a hill\u2014was overwhelming. Then, cresting the hill at 19th Street, a flash of insight for a flat-pack chair design clicked into place. She realized this commute wasn't a chore. It was an inhalation of ideas, a physical momentum that powered her mind. This city was already working with her.\n\n4.\nAt her SoMa office, she wrestled for weeks with a recycled polymer that felt cold and lifeless. Frustrated, she stared at the gray swatch and suddenly recalled the subtle, cross-hatched texture of her mother\u2019s embroidery on a linen tablecloth. The next day, she proposed a new mold with a delicate, embossed pattern. It transformed the material, giving it warmth and tactile grace. It was a tiny victory that proved her mother\u2019s art had a function her father would have deeply admired.\n\n5.\nIt was at a small gallery opening in Dogpatch last year. She stood before an installation of glowing lampshades, each one grown from mycelium. They were organic, unrepeatable, and perfectly functional. In that moment, watching the soft light filter through the fungal structures, she felt a profound sense of recognition. This was it. The vague ambition of her own studio sharpened into a clear, urgent pull\u2014a need to create not just from recycled materials, but from life itself."
